# Triads {#sec-triads}





## Types of Undirected Triads {#sec-triads}

We could do the same thing we did with dyads (subgraphs of order two) with the different *subgraphs of order three* in an undirected graph. These are called **undirected triads**.



::: {.cell fig-cap-location='margin'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A null triad.](lesson-graphs-triads_files/figure-html/fig-triads1-1.png){#fig-triads1 width=480}
:::
:::


Take for instance, the subgraph defined by nodes *B*, *C*, and *F* in the graph shown in @fig-undirected. This is shown in @fig-triads1. It shows three people who are not connected to one another! Like strangers in a park sitting on three different benches. This is called the **null triad**.


::: {.cell fig-cap-location='margin'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A disconnected triad](lesson-graphs-triads_files/figure-html/fig-triads2-1.png){#fig-triads2 width=480}
:::
:::


Now let's define a subgraph using nodes *A*, *C*, and *E*. The resulting triad is shown in @fig-triads2. Now this looks like a pair of friends *A* and *C*, in the same room with a stranger (*E*) whom they are not acquainted with. You may have experienced this before at a social gathering. This is called the **disconnected triad**. It is disconnected, because the subgraph formed by the three nodes is disconnected, as defined earlier; there is no way that either *A* or *C* can reach *E*, given that *E* is an isolate in the subgraph.


::: {.cell fig-cap-location='margin'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![An open triad.](lesson-graphs-triads_files/figure-html/fig-triads3-1.png){#fig-triads3 width=480}
:::
:::


We can continue. Let's define a subgraph from the larger graph in shown in @fig-undirected, but this time we will pick nodes *A*, *B*, and *C*. What comes out? This is shown in @fig-triads3. This time, there is one person, node *A*, who is acquainted with two other people, nodes *B* and *C*, but they don't seem to know one another. It's like when you have friends from work and friends from school who have never met. This is called the **open triad**, because even though the subgraph is connected (there are no isolate nodes like in @fig-triads2, there is a "open hole" in the triad separating nodes *B* and *C*. Perhaps *A* should introduce their friends to one another!


::: {.cell fig-cap-location='margin'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![A closed triad.](lesson-graphs-triads_files/figure-html/fig-triads4-1.png){#fig-triads4 width=480}
:::
:::


One last one. Let's define a subgraph from @fig-undirected, but this time let's pick nodes *A*, *D*, and *F*. The result is shown in @fig-triads4. Now we have three friends all of whom know one another! So there are three distinct pairs of relations in the triad: *AD*, *AF* and *DF*. 

@fig-triads4 is what we would see for that group of three friends that always seems to hang out together. This is called the **closed triad**, because there is no room to add more links to it. It is also called the closed triad because it is the configuration you get when you add a final link to the open triad (thus "closing" it). As discussed in @sec-indirect, a closed triad is also a **cycle** of length three.


::: {.cell fig-cap-location='margin'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![The four types of undirected triads.](lesson-graphs-triads_files/figure-html/fig-undir-triads-1.png){#fig-undir-triads width=960}
:::
:::


@fig-undir-triads shows the four types of undirected triads using unlabeled subgraphs. The key point is that in an undirected graph, there can only be these *four* types of triads. So every threesome of actors is part of a **null**, **disconnected**, **open**, or **closed** triad. 

All four triads are subgraphs of the same order (three), but they are different in size. The null triad is size zero, the disconnected triad is size one, the open triad is size two, and the closed triad is size three. 

Dyads, triads, and subgraphs of higher order (called **network motifs**) are the *building blocks* of larger network structures in society [@milo02].

